# 2018-06-20 
    COM Server - Critical Error logged @ Windows Event Viewer:
        "
        The application-specific permission settings do not grant Local Activation permission for the COM Server application with CLSID 
        {...}
         and APPID 
        {...}
         to the user NT AUTHORITY\LOCAL SERVICE SID (S-1-5-19) from address LocalHost (Using LRPC) running in the application container Unavailable SID (Unavailable). This security permission can be modified using the Component Services administrative tool.
         "

    FIX:
        1. RegEdit.exe; navigate to and change owner/ACLs of the two problem keys reported by Event Viewer (as above); Properties > Security > Advanced ... change OWNER for problem object AND ALL THEREUNDER.

            HKCR\CLSID\{...}
            HKCR\APPID\{...}

        2. DCOMCNFG.exe (Component Services) app per @ cmd.exe as Admin. Navigate to: Component Services > Computer > My Computer > DCOM Config. Click on that object launched a query window informing that "... not registered ..." and asking to register it; clicked "yes". This process repeated several times, after which the right-hand panel of populated with all the apps handled thereunder.
        
        REF: https://shauncassells.wordpress.com/2015/09/28/windows-10-event-10016-fix-the-application-specific-permission-settings-do-not-grant-local-activation-permission-for-the-com-server-application-with-clsid-d63b10c5-bb46-4990-a94f-e40b9d520160-and-a/
        
            Note @ ref. article author's experience, there was no popup-query-answer window @ DCOMCNFG.exe. Rather, changed owner/ACLs of the two registry keys of the logged error message to "Administrators" group. and @ DCOMCNFG.exe, changed "RunTimeBroker" ACLs per: Properties > Security > "Launch and Activation Permissions" > Edit ACLs to grant Full access to SYSTEM. 
            
            RunTimeBroker changes will NOT BE ALLOWED unless Administrators group has owner/access per their CLSID keys; use RegEdit process detailed above to take Owner/ACLs. 
            
            RunTimeBrokers (2) are apps that handles permissions for Universal Apps; its service is called Time Broker; cannot be disabled.

# 2018-05-31 (post Windows Update)
    cmdadmin.exe scheme per Directory @ File Explorer, "CMD (Admin) Here", is ruined; cmdadmin.exe was a clone of cmd.exe set to always run as Admin, and called from a relevant registry key; now treated as an unknown program; "Not enough storage is available to process this command." ... and such msgs.
    
    FIX: 
        - Create binary wrapper using golang, which calls batch script, and reference that binary in the apropos registry key. Set binary to always run as administrator: Properties > Compatibility > "Change settings for all users" > "Run this program as an administrator".
    
    Corrupted Windows Defender file @ "C:\Program Files\Windows Defender\MpClient.dll" Error Message on boot: "Bad image ..." regarding MpClient.dll @ MSASCuil.exe
    
    FIX:
        - Extracted last-good version @ system WIM (captured per DISM @ WinPE)
        - Take Ownership and change ACLs
        - Overwrite corrupted with last-good version.

